{"title_page": "Beaduheard", "text_new": "'''Beaduheard''' was an [[Anglo-Saxon]] [[reeve]] who was based in [[Dorchester]] in [[Dorset]], who in 787 became the first known person killed by a [[Viking]] raid in England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medievalists.net/2011/11/england-and-the-vikings/|title=England and the Vikings|date=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNothing is known of Beaduheard's early life, including where he was born or who his parents were. However, his name (Beaduheard means 'battle-hard')<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://gohighbrow.com/probing-attacks-england-scotland-and-ireland/|title=Probing Attacks: England, Scotland, and Ireland|date=June 11, 2018|website=Highbrow}}</ref> and position suggests that his family were of relatively high rank, from a martial background, and that he was over the age of 31, which is regarded as middle aged for the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.viking.no/e/england/york/life_expectancy_in_jorvik.html|title=Life expectancy in Jorvik|website=www.viking.no}}</ref>. He was reeve during the reign of [[Beorhtric of Wessex]], king of [[Wessex]] from 786 to 802.\n\n==Death==\nThe [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]] for AD 787 reports the following.<ref name=giles19>Giles Tr., J.A, ed. Six Old English Chronicles: \u00c6thelweard's Chronicle. p. 19</ref>\n\n{{cquote|AD 787 \u2013 This year king Bertric took to wife Eadburga, king Offa's daughter; and in his days first came three ships of Northmen, out of H\u00e6retha-land [Denmark]. And then the reeve rode to the place, and would have driven them to the king's town, because he knew not who they were: and they there slew him. These were the first ships of Danishmen which sought the land of the English nation.}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:The_Anglo-Saxon_Chronicle_(Giles).djvu/57|title=Page:The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle (Giles).djvu/57 - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.wikisource.org}}</ref>\n\n[[\u00c6thelweard (historian)|\u00c6thelweard's]] version of the Chronicle, known as the ''[[Chronicon \u00c6thelweardi]]'', a Latin translation of a lost version of the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, goes into more detail. He tells us that the three ships landed at [[Portland]] and that when Beaduheard heard of the their arrival he \"leapt on his horse\" and \"sped to the harbour with a few men\". He also claims that Beaduheard spoke to the arrivals in an \"authorative tone\" and this is why they killed him.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MIHfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT199&lpg=PT199&dq=beaduheard&source=bl&ots=DZjeeuC0kC&sig=ACfU3U1e5Ki8yqR-Wr-cM2ICEYZAt7--mQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmjMrfqP7oAhVTe8AKHSgNAyE4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=beaduheard&f=false|title=Danes in Wessex: The Scandinavian Impact on Southern England, c. 800\u2013c. 1100|first1=Ryan|last1=Lavelle|first2=Simon|last2=Roffey|date=November 30, 2015|publisher=Oxbow Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n\u00c6thelweard was writing over 100 years after the event, sometime after 975 and probably before 983.<ref>Miller, Sean, \"\u00c6thelweard\" in The Blackwell Encyclopaedia of Anglo-Saxon England, ed. Michael Lapidge, 2001</ref> His account is the first to name Beaduheard, however as his work was a Latin translation of a (now lost) Anglo-Saxon original there is nothing to suggest that the name is incorrect. He does give the origin of the attackers as Norway rather than Denmark, specifying that they came from [[Hordaland]] (near modern day [[Bergen]]). This difference could indicate that there was confusion about the true identities of the raiding party, and that they can only really be said to have been foreigners, probably from somewhere across the North Sea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erenow.net/postclassical/viking-britain/1.php|title=Outsiders from Across the Water - Viking Britain|website=erenow.net}}</ref>\n\nThe apparent poor preparation of Beaduheard and way in which he and his men were seemingly surprised by the attack has led to this being referred to as the first contact between the Vikings and England<ref name=\"auto1\"/>, however as the historian [[Tom Shippey]] has pointed out this is unlikely to have been the first ever contact with Vikings, either from [[Norway]] or [[Denmark]], as \"they must have been sniffing round the shores of Britain for some time, maybe in the far north for as long as a generation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aX5fDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT56&lpg=PT56&dq=beaduheard&source=bl&ots=qaqp3lrH_m&sig=ACfU3U0-N4s4eCk4RUKlVH6cz46GoZtK6A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmjMrfqP7oAhVTe8AKHSgNAyE4ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=beaduheard&f=false|title=Laughing Shall I Die: Lives and Deaths of the Great Vikings|first=Tom|last=Shippey|date=May 15, 2018|publisher=Reaktion Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> It is possible that this was a raiding party, however \u00c6thelweards' suggestion that the Saxons were attacked due to Beaduheards \"authoritative tone\" could suggest a misunderstanding. It seems likely that the two groups did not speak each others language, and thus could not understand each other. In addition Beaduheard was trying to bring the new group back to Dorchester, 12 miles from their landing place<ref name=\"auto\"/>, which may have led to conflict.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSix years later, in 793, a major Viking raid took place on the monastery of [[Lindisfarne]] in the kingdom of [[Northumberland]]. This is has commonly been regarded as the start of the Viking raids on Britain, which only ended (in England at least) in 1066 with the [[Battle of Stamford Bridge]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxon England]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxons killed in battle]]\n[[Category:Viking Age in the British Isles]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:787 deaths]]\n[[Category:8th-century English people]]\n[[Category:8th century in England]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "'''Beaduheard''' was an [[Anglo-Saxon]] [[reeve]] who was based in [[Dorchester]] in [[Dorset]], who in 787 became the first known person killed by a [[Viking]] raid in England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medievalists.net/2011/11/england-and-the-vikings/|title=England and the Vikings|date=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNothing is known of Beaduheard's early life, including where he was born or who his parents were. However, his name (Beaduheard means 'battle-hard')<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://gohighbrow.com/probing-attacks-england-scotland-and-ireland/|title=Probing Attacks: England, Scotland, and Ireland|date=June 11, 2018|website=Highbrow}}</ref> and position suggests that his family were of relatively high rank, from a martial background, and that he was over the age of 31, which is regarded as middle aged for the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.viking.no/e/england/york/life_expectancy_in_jorvik.html|title=Life expectancy in Jorvik|website=www.viking.no}}</ref>. He was reeve during the reign of [[Beorhtric of Wessex]], king of [[Wessex]] from 786 to 802.\n\n==Death==\nThe [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]] for AD 787 reports the following.<ref name=giles19>Giles Tr., J.A, ed. Six Old English Chronicles: \u00c6thelweard's Chronicle. p. 19</ref>\n\n{{cquote|AD 787 \u2013 This year king Bertric took to wife Eadburga, king Offa's daughter; and in his days first came three ships of Northmen, out of H\u00e6retha-land [Denmark]. And then the reeve rode to the place, and would have driven them to the king's town, because he knew not who they were: and they there slew him. These were the first ships of Danishmen which sought the land of the English nation.}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:The_Anglo-Saxon_Chronicle_(Giles).djvu/57|title=Page:The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle (Giles).djvu/57 - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.wikisource.org}}</ref>\n\n[[\u00c6thelweard (historian)|\u00c6thelweard's]] version of the Chronicle, known as the ''[[Chronicon \u00c6thelweardi]]'', a Latin translation of a lost version of the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, goes into more detail. He tells us that the three ships landed at [[Portland]] and that when Beaduheard heard of the their arrival he \"leapt on his horse\" and \"sped to the harbour with a few men\". He also claims that Beaduheard spoke to the arrivals in an \"authorative tone\" and this is why they killed him.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MIHfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT199&lpg=PT199&dq=beaduheard&source=bl&ots=DZjeeuC0kC&sig=ACfU3U1e5Ki8yqR-Wr-cM2ICEYZAt7--mQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmjMrfqP7oAhVTe8AKHSgNAyE4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=beaduheard&f=false|title=Danes in Wessex: The Scandinavian Impact on Southern England, c. 800\u2013c. 1100|first1=Ryan|last1=Lavelle|first2=Simon|last2=Roffey|date=November 30, 2015|publisher=Oxbow Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n\u00c6thelweard was writing over 100 years after the event, sometime after 975 and probably before 983.<ref>Miller, Sean, \"\u00c6thelweard\" in The Blackwell Encyclopaedia of Anglo-Saxon England, ed. Michael Lapidge, 2001</ref> His account is the first to name Beaduheard, however as his work was a Latin translation of a (now lost) Anglo-Saxon original there is nothing to suggest that the name is incorrect. He does give the origin of the attackers as Norway rather than Denmark, specifying that they came from [[Hordaland]] (near modern day [[Bergen]]). This difference could indicate that there was confusion about the true identities of the raiding party, and that they can only really be said to have been foreigners, probably from somewhere across the North Sea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erenow.net/postclassical/viking-britain/1.php|title=Outsiders from Across the Water - Viking Britain|website=erenow.net}}</ref>\n\nThe apparent poor preparation of Beaduheard and way in which he and his men were seemingly surprised by the attack has led to this being referred to as the first contact between the Vikings and England<ref name=\"auto1\"/>, however as the historian [[Tom Shippey]] has pointed out this is unlikely to have been the first ever contact with Vikings, either from [[Norway]] or [[Denmark]], as \"they must have been sniffing round the shores of Britain for some time, maybe in the far north for as long as a generation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aX5fDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT56&lpg=PT56&dq=beaduheard&source=bl&ots=qaqp3lrH_m&sig=ACfU3U0-N4s4eCk4RUKlVH6cz46GoZtK6A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjmjMrfqP7oAhVTe8AKHSgNAyE4ChDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=beaduheard&f=false|title=Laughing Shall I Die: Lives and Deaths of the Great Vikings|first=Tom|last=Shippey|date=May 15, 2018|publisher=Reaktion Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> It is possible that this was a raiding party, however \u00c6thelweards' suggestion that the Saxons were attacked due to Beaduheards \"authoritative tone\" could suggest a misunderstanding. It seems likely that the two groups did not speak each others language, and thus could not understand each other. In addition Beaduheard was trying to bring the new group back to Dorchester, 12 miles from their landing place<ref name=\"auto\"/>, which may have led to conflict.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSix years later, in 793, a major Viking raid took place on the monastery of [[Lindisfarne]] in the kingdom of [[Northumberland]]. This is has commonly been regarded as the start of the Viking raids on Britain, which only ended (in England at least) in 1066 with the [[Battle of Stamford Bridge]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxon England]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxons killed in battle]]\n[[Category:Viking age in the British Isles]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:787 deaths]]\n[[Category:8th-century English people]]\n[[Category:8th century in England]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Nickuae", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaduheard"}
